'''Extra Life''' is a [[fundraising]] event,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = About Extra Life|url = http://www.extra-life.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=cms.page&id=1197|website = Children's Miracle Network Hospitals|accessdate = ffjb2015-09-14}}</ref> the proceeds of which go to branches of the [[Children's Miracle Network Hospitals]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = History {{!}} Children's Miracle Network Hospitals|url = http://childrensmiraclenetworkhospitals.org/About|website = childrensmiraclenetworkhospitals.org|accessdate = 2015-09-14}}</ref> 100% of all donations go directly to the hospitals.<ref name=":0" />
Extra Life was formed in 2008 to honor Victoria {{proper name|Enmon}}, who died of [[acute lymphoblastic leukemia]]. It was aided by the [[Sarcastic Gamer]] community, who sent gifts and video games to her.
The main premise of the event is that group or teams get together and play different types of games for a 24 hour marathon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/sponsor-story/uvm-medical-center/2018/10/31/hundreds-across-region-expected-participate-annual-extra-life-event/1806615002/|title=Hundreds across the region expected to participate in annual “Extra Life” event|last=|first=|date=October 31, 2018|work=Burlington Free Press|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref> Many of these users will live-stream their game-play and activities on the platform Twitch. During this process, players will ask for donations that will then be sent to Children's Miracle Network Hospitals. Groups that participate range from [[Austin, Texas]] media company [[Rooster Teeth]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/rooster-teeth-extra-life/|title=Rooster Teeth's 24-Hour Extra Life Stream Brings the Pain—For Charity|last=Schroeder|first=Audra|date=2018-11-09|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> to [[East Carolina University]] Board Gaming Society<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theeastcarolinian.com/arts_and_entertainment/article_8ec41158-e519-11e8-b5bf-f752fbf0f8ff.html|title=Gaming group gathers to fundraise for Children’s Miracle Network|last=Spade|first=Katherine|work=The East Carolinian|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref>, and donations are given through cash or credit donation. Many participants have connections to the hospitals that they chose to highlight and donate their proceeds to and some donation pages continue to accept donations until December 31 of the year of the event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cleburnetimesreview.com/news/father-son-team-up-for-cook-children-s/article_49416200-e46c-11e8-9aa3-23974467ba1a.html|title=Father, son team up for Cook Children’s|last=services|first=Lisa Magers/cisd community|work=Cleburne Times-Review|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref>
