'''''Louis Riel''''' is a historical biography in [[comics]] by Canadian cartoonist [[Chester Brown]], published as a book in 2003 after serializion in 1999–2003.  The story deals with [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] rebel leader [[Louis Riel]]'s antagonistic relationship with the newly established [[Canadian Confederation|Canadian government]].  It begins shortly before the 1869 [[Red River Rebellion]], and ends with Riel's 1885 hanging for [[Treason Act 1351|high treason]].  The book explores Riel's possible [[schizophrenia]]—he believed God had named him Prophet of the New World, destined to lead the Métis people to freedom.

The work is noted for its emotional disengagement, its intentionally flat dialogue, and a minimalist drawing style inspired by that of [[Harold Gray]]'s comic strip ''[[Little Orphan Annie]]''.  Unusual for comics of the time, it includes a full scholarly apparatus: a foreword, index, bibliography, and end notes.  The lengthy, hand-lettered appendix provides insight into Brown's creative process and biases and highlights where he changed historical facts to create a more engaging story, such as incorporating a conspiracy theory not widely accepted by historians.  Brown became interested in the issue of property rights while researching the book, which led to a public change in his politics from [[anarchism]] to [[libertarianism]].

Although Brown intended it to be published only in book form, his publisher had him first serialize ''Louis Riel'' as a comic book, which lasted ten issues.  The series was the first comic book to receive a grant from the [[Canada Council|Canada Council for the Arts]].  It won a favourable critical reception and three [[Harvey Award]]s.  The serialization sold poorly, but the book version was a surprise bestseller.  Its success played a major part in gaining shelf space for serious [[graphic novel]]s in mainstream North American bookstores.

{{TOC limit|3}}

==Overview==

Subtitled "A Comic-Strip Biography",{{sfn|MacDonald|2012|p=56}} ''Louis Riel'' looks at [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] rebel leader [[Louis Riel]] and his leadership in the [[Red River Rebellion|Red River]] and [[North-West Rebellion|North-West]] rebellions.  It does not attempt a complete retelling of Riel's life—it omits long periods and ignores many aspects of his personality.  Instead the focus is on his "antagonistic relationship with the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]]"{{sfn|Hutcheon|2010|p=47}} from 1869 to 1885.{{sfn|Booker|2010|p=370}}  The story comprises 241 pages of the 271-page book, and is supplemented with a complete [[Critical apparatus|scholarly apparatus]]: a foreword, bibliography, [[index (publishing)|index]], map section and extensive end notes.{{sfnm|1a1=Hutcheon|1y=2010|1p=47|2a1=Marshall|2y=2005|3a1=MacDonald|3y=2012|3pp=57–58}}  It has strong [[Historiography|historiographical]] elements, detailing in the appendix the research done and choices made by the author in developing a story.{{sfn|MacDonald|2012|pp=57–58}}

Brown grew up in the Canadian province of [[Quebec]], where the majority speaks French, and where Riel is often considered a martyr.  However Brown, who grew up speaking only English,{{sfn|Weisblott|2008}} said he was largely ignorant of Riel's story{{Sfn|Sim|2003a|p=23}} until he read [[Maggie Siggins]]' 1994 biography ''Louis Riel: A Life of Revolution''.{{sfnm|1a1=Hajdu|1y=2009/2010|2a1=Epp|2y=2002}}  Many of Brown's favourite topics are entwined in ''Louis Riel'': [[anti-authoritarianism]], outsider religion, [[insanity]], and accuracy and objectivity in nonfiction.{{Sfn|Arnold|2003-05-30}}  A central incident in the book is an eight-panel sequence in which Riel has a revelatory experience on a hilltop in Washington, D.C.  He experiences visions and talks to God, who declares him Prophet of the New World and instructs him to lead his people to freedom.  On the cover of the book, however, we see Riel standing alone in the wilderness, staring into the sky, leaving open the question of whether what he witnessed was real.{{sfn|Wolk|2007|p=155}}

==Background==

{{Quote box
|quote  = "I read {{interp|''Louis Riel: A Life of Revolution''}} and thought, 'That's a good dramatic story—it'd make a good strip.'"
|source = Chester Brown, interview with [[Dave Sim]] (2003){{sfnm|1a1=Sim|1y=2003a|1p=23|2a1=Hajdu|2y=2009/2010}}
|width = 25em}}

In 1995, Brown published the [[anti-psychiatry]] comics essay "[[The Little Man (comics)#My Mom was a Schizophrenic|My Mom was a Schizophrenic]]", in which he examines society's role in mental illness, and questions the medical profession's accepted beliefs about it.{{sfn|Kreiner|2004}}  The six-page strip came with two pages of end notes gathered from his research.  Brown enjoyed this project and thought he would like to take on another in which he could "cram a lot of research into a comic strip".{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}}  When he came across Siggins' biography of Riel, he had been working on the experimental ''[[Underwater (comics)|Underwater]]'' series, a project on which he felt he had lost his way.{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=162}}  His father died in late 1997, and he decided he did not "want to waste {{interp|his}} time with projects that weren't working out".{{sfn|Tousley|2005}}  In 1998, he turned his attention to Riel,{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}} putting the unpopular ''Underwater'' series on hold.{{sfn|Arnold|2004-06-28}}

While researching, Brown came across two books by political scientist [[Tom Flanagan (political scientist)|Tom Flanagan]]: ''Louis "David" Riel: "Prophet of the New World"'' (1996) and ''Louis Riel and the Rebellion: 1885 Reconsidered'' (2000).  Brown found ''"Prophet of the New World"'' particularly intriguing as it dealt with Riel's religious ideas while reevaluating his alleged diagnosis of mental illness,{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=164}} two topics Brown had especial interest in, as he had previously made "eccentric" [[Chester Brown's Gospel adaptations|adaptations of the Gospel]], and comics dealing with his mother's [[schizophrenia]].{{sfn|Wolk|2004}}  He also came across books by researcher Don McLean and historian Douglas N. Sprague that advanced the [[conspiracy theory]] that the 1885 North-West Rebellion was deliberately provoked by Prime Minister [[John A. Macdonald]] to gain support for the building of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway#Building the railway, 1881–1885|transcontinental railway]].{{sfn|Bell|2006|pp=164–165}}

Brown had gained a reputation for improvised storytelling by the time he began work on ''Louis Riel''.  With ''Underwater'', he had intended to write a script, but in the end chose to improvise.  He found the results unsatisfactory, and decided to write a full script beforehand for his next project.  The script for ''Louis Riel'' came to over 200 pages.{{sfnm|1a1=Epp|1y=2002|2a1=Wivel|2y=2011b}}

Brown's was not the first depiction of the Métis leader in comics.  [[James Simpkins]], a Canadian cartoonist best known for Jasper the Bear, made a mildly anti-Riel two-page strip in 1967,{{sfn|Brown|May 2002|p=25}} and Pierre Dupuis produced a French-language two-page summary in 1979.{{sfn|Brown|October 2002|p=24}}  A 23-page pro-Riel strip appeared in ''Canadian History Comic Book No. 2: Rebellion'' in 1972.{{sfn|Brown|February 2003|p=24}}  In 1980, Italian artist [[Hugo Pratt]] created a character called [[Jesuit Joe]] who was supposed to have descended from Riel.{{sfn|Paquin|2006|p=8}}  Publishing house Les Éditions des Plaines published two books on Riel: Robert Freynet's 58-page {{lang|fr|Louis Riel en bande dessinée}}{{efn
|{{cite book
  |first     = Robert
  |last      = Freynet
  |title     = Louis Riel en bande dessinée
  |isbn      = 978-0-920944-92-9
  |language  = French
  |publisher = Les Éditions des Plaines
  |year      = 1990}}
}} (''"Louis Riel in Comics"'') in 1990,{{sfn|Brown|October 2002|p=24}} and Zoran and Toufik's {{lang|fr|Louis Riel, le père du Manitoba}}{{efn
|{{cite book
  |author1   = Zoran
  |author2   = Toufik
  |title     = Louis Riel, le père du Manitoba
  |isbn      = 2-921353-44-X
  |publisher = Les Éditions des Plaines
  |year      = 1996}}
}} (''"Louis Riel, the Father of Manitoba"'') in 1996, both in French.{{sfnm|1a1=Brown|1y=May 2002|1p=25|2a1=Paquin|2y=2006|2p=8}}  Riel also played a secondary role in the 1995 [[Franco-Belgian comics|comic album]] {{lang|fr|Le crépuscule des Bois-Brûlés}}{{efn
|{{cite book
  |first     = Christian
  |last      = Quesnel
